‘Most cheating-free’ election
Mr Kyagulanyi’s claim that the election was rigged is most odd if placed side-by-side with Mr Museveni’s claim Saturday night that what Ugandans had just gone through could turn out to be the “most cheating-free” election in Uganda’s history.
Mr Museveni said one of Uganda’s chronic problems had been cheating in elections, which he said had been done through ballot-box stuffing, multiple voting, and other methods. He said this had been significantly eliminated by the biometric machines that were used in the latest election.
He took a jibe at the old parties, saying the Uganda People’s Congress (UPC) thrived on multiple voting in 1962, citing the example of his late friend and comrade Eriya Kategaya, whom he said was under age in 1962 but voted eight times in favour of UPC.
He also castigated the Kabaka Yekka party which he accused of intimidating the Democratic Party (DP) in 1962.
Manipulating elections
But all these are the same accusations which have been levelled against Mr Museveni and his party over the years with his re-election being challenged in 2001, 2006, and 2016. Mr Museveni’s party has also been accused of using money to manipulate elections.



